South African Stocks Climb; Impala and Northam Both Rise as Platinum Gains

-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s   a n d   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n
-- 
2011-04-29T16:01:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-29/south-african-equities-ifca-technologies-anglogold-shares-move.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
climbed 176.28, or 0.5 percent, to 32,836.23 at the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg. The index advanced 0.5 percent this week.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
company, fell for the third day, losing 3.12 rand, or 1.12
percent, to 274.50 rand. Copper dropped in  Shanghai , set for a
second monthly decline, on concern that the government’s
measures to tame inflation and cool the  property market  will
weigh on demand in the world’s largest metals user.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the world’s second-
biggest producer of the metal, climbed 1.53 rand, or 0.8
percent, to 205.03 rand. The company’s Zimbabwe unit posted a 15
percent increase in profit in its fiscal third quarter, helped
by metal price gains, even as the government boosted royalty
rates.  Northam Platinum Ltd. (NHM)  , the operator of the world’s
deepest platinum mine rose 70 cents, or 1.6 percent, to 43.30
rand. Platinum gained 0.3 percent to $1,846.75 an ounce.  Pick n Pay Stores Ltd. (PIK)  ,  South Africa ’s second-
biggest retailer, advanced 14 cents, or 0.3 percent, to 42.51
rand. Chairman Gareth Ackerman bought about 1.1 million rand of
shares in the retailer, according to a statement from the
company.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose for the fifth day in six, gaining 80 cents,
or 0.2 percent, to 379 rand. Futures traded near a 31-month high
after purchases climbed in March as Americans spent more on food
and fuel, according to a Commerce Department report.  To contact the reporters on this story:
